# Design Specs

## Figma

Design a multi-screen web app called “OrbitUMD,” a UMD-focused academic planning tool. The visual style and UX should be consistent across all screens.

GLOBAL STYLE
- Overall vibe: modern, clean, friendly, “UMD tech platform” rather than a personal project.
- Layout: desktop-first responsive web app, with a left navigation column and main content area where appropriate, but onboarding can be full-screen modals.
- Color: dark UI. Background is a very dark charcoal (not pure black). Accent colors inspired by UMD (reds, golds) but kept slightly muted so UI feels professional. Use bright accent colors for primary CTAs and status pills (e.g., green = completed, blue = in progress).
- Typography: sans-serif, modern, bright, slightly thick letters for main headings. These headings should have a subtle outer glow or soft shadow to pop against the dark background. Body text is lighter-weight, high contrast, easy to read.
- Components: rounded cards, clear labels, subtle shadows. Every button and page should have a short descriptive subtitle or helper text so the app feels extremely well explained and approachable.
- Iconography: simple line icons where helpful (info, help, edit, link, calendar, degree cap, checklist).

---

SCREEN 1: ONBOARDING WELCOME

Purpose: First-time welcome.

Content:
- Full-screen dark background (charcoal).
- Centered card or centered column layout.

Elements:
- Large title: “Welcome to OrbitUMD”
- Subtitle (catchy, clear premise): e.g.
  “Plan your four-year journey, build smarter schedules, and never lose track of a single requirement.”
- Short body text block explaining in 1–2 sentences:
  “OrbitUMD is your all‑in‑one planner for UMD. Import credits, map out majors and minors, explore Gen Eds, and generate class schedules that actually fit your life.”
- Primary CTA button: “Let’s get started”
- Secondary button (lower emphasis): “Sign in” / “Log in” (assume they’re not yet authenticated but keep it optional).
- Small helper text at bottom: “You can change your plan at any time — OrbitUMD updates everything automatically.”

Style:
- “OrbitUMD” in the hero should use the thicker, bright-font-with-shadow treatment.
- Subtle background treatment (e.g., soft abstract orbital shapes, faint planet rings, or dots) behind content to suggest ‘orbit’ but not distract.

---

SCREEN 2: ONBOARDING – BASIC PROFILE INPUT

After clicking “Let’s get started,” show a multi-step onboarding form. This is Step 1.

Content:
- Title at top: “Let’s get started”
- Subtitle: “Tell us the basics so we can build the right plan for you.”

Form fields (grouped in a card centered on screen):
- Full Name (text input)
- UMD Email (school email, with placeholder like “yourid@umd.edu”)
- UMD UID (short numeric input)
- Degree type (dropdown): e.g. “B.S. / B.A. / Double Degree / Second Major”
- Primary Major (dropdown or searchable dropdown)
- Additional Majors (optional multi-select)
- Minors (optional multi-select)
- Starting semester (dropdown, default to next upcoming term, e.g. “Fall 2026”)
- Expected graduation year (optional dropdown)
- Checkbox or toggle: “I’m a new student (no previous college credits)” vs “I have previous credits (AP, transfer, etc.)”

Controls:
- Progress indicator at top (e.g., “Step 1 of 4: Basic Info”) with a thin progress bar.
- Primary button: “Continue”
- Secondary button: “Back” (disabled on first step) and a “Skip for now” link for non-essential fields.

UX notes:
- Each field has a short helper line under it explaining what it’s used for.
- Small tooltip icon next to “Degree type,” “Additional Majors,” and “Minors” explaining that these can be edited later in Settings.

