SCREEN 3: ONBOARDING – “WHAT’S YOUR GOAL RIGHT NOW?”

This is a hub screen that defines the main flows. Use a near-black background with four large, well-spaced cards/buttons.

Title:
- “What’s your goal right now?”

Subtitle:
- “OrbitUMD can be as lightweight or as in‑depth as you need. Pick what you want to do today. You can always explore the other options later.”

Layout:
- 4 large cards (2x2 grid on desktop; stacked on mobile). Each card is clickable and has:
  - Title
  - Small image or illustrative icon
  - 1–2 sentence description
  - Small label/chip like “Quick” vs “Guided” to signal complexity.

CARD 1: “Generate Schedule”
- Label: “Quick · Like UMD’s Venus”
- Description: “Already know which classes you want? Plug them in and let OrbitUMD generate possible schedules — just like Venus, but cleaner. Filter by days, times, and format, then pick the schedule that fits your life.”
- Click → takes user to a Venus-style schedule generator screen.

CARD 2: “Explore Schedules”
- Better name: “Build My Week” (Feel free to choose between “Explore Schedules” and “Build My Week”, but emphasize exploratory scheduling.)
- Label: “Interactive · Calendar View”
- Description: “Search UMD courses, drag them onto a weekly calendar, and experiment with different combinations before you commit. Perfect for exploring what’s even possible this term.”
- Click → takes user to a calendar-based schedule builder similar to Jupiterp’s Course Planner.

CARD 3: “Make a Four-Year Plan”
- Label: “Guided · Full Degree Planner”
- Description: “Map out your entire degree — Gen Eds, majors, minors, and electives — across every semester. We’ll walk you through your credits, requirements, and a clean four-year plan view.”
- Click → starts a guided setup flow (AP/transfer credits, Gen Eds, major requirements) before showing the four-year plan grid.

CARD 4: “View My Degree Audit”
- Label: “Overview · Progress Snapshot”
- Description: “See a clear, interactive view of what you’ve completed, what’s in progress, and what’s left. Click any requirement to see course options or jump directly into planning.”
- Click → takes user to the Degree Audit-style overview (OrbitUMD’s clean, linked version of the UMD audit).

At bottom:
- Link: “Skip for now, take me to the dashboard” (for power users).

