GLOBAL NAVIGATION & EXPLANATORY UX

Once onboarding is complete, show a persistent top bar and left nav.

Top bar:
- OrbitUMD logo/wordmark on left.
- Term selector, search (for courses, requirements).
- Profile menu on right (name, email, link to Settings).

Left nav items:
- “Dashboard” – quick summary and shortcuts.
- “Generate Schedule”
- “Build My Week”
- “Four-Year Plan”
- “Degree Audit”
- “Gen Eds”
- “Settings”

Dashboard:
- Cards for:
  - “Next semester status”: courses locked in, total credits.
  - “Requirements snapshot”: key bars (Gen Eds, primary major).
  - “Suggested next steps” (e.g., “Add your Physics major requirements”, “Plan Fall 2027 classes”).

Help & clarity:
- Each major page has a top “info strip” with a one-line explanation and a small “Learn more” link that opens a quick walkthrough modal.
- Use small “i” tooltips next to complex concepts: “Upper Level Concentration”, “Choose X from Y”, “AND/OR group”.
- All buttons and icons should have clear labels or tooltips describing exactly what they do.

---

GENERAL INTERACTION NOTES

- Use consistent status colors: green = completed, blue = in progress, grey = planned, red/orange = missing/unfulfilled.
- Use subtle animations for transitions between onboarding steps and when new sections are added.
- Ensure all screen designs feel visually unified: same dark background, same bright-thick headline font with shadow, consistent card and button styling.

Generate full screen layouts for:
1. Welcome to OrbitUMD (onboarding hero).
2. Basic Profile Input (Step 1).
3. “What’s your goal right now?” goal selection with 4 large cards.
4. Generate Schedule (Venus-style).
5. Build My Week (calendar-based planner).
6. Credit Import screen for AP/transfer/exams.
7. Gen Eds overview with filterable table.
8. [Major] Degree Requirements builder with sections and AND/OR grouping.
9. Degree Audit summary page with clickable requirements and course chips.
10. Four-Year Plan grid with semesters and tabs for Requirements, Gen Eds, Credits.
11. Main Dashboard with left nav and summary cards.

Keep the visual hierarchy very clear and explanatory text prominent, so a brand-new UMD student can understand each page and button without prior context.
